   (Message) The crash is caused by a buffer overflow in
   `CWE122_Heap_Based_Buffer_Overflow__char_type_overrun_memcpy_01_bad`, located
   in `program.c`.
   
   ### Analysis of the Defect
   
   Lines 36-42 of `program.c`:
   ```c
   36: charVoid * structCharVoid = (charVoid *)malloc(sizeof(charVoid));
   ...
   42: memcpy(structCharVoid->charFirst, SRC_STR, sizeof(*structCharVoid));
   ```
   
   The `charVoid` struct is defined as:
   ```c
   typedef struct _charVoid
   {
       char charFirst[16];
       void * voidSecond;
       void * voidThird;
   } charVoid;
   ```
   `sizeof(charVoid)` is larger than 16 bytes (it includes the array and at
   least two pointers, e.g., $16 + 8 + 8 = 32$ bytes on a 64-bit system).
   
   When `memcpy` is called with `sizeof(*structCharVoid)` as the size argument
   at line 42, it attempts to copy `sizeof(charVoid)` bytes into
   `structCharVoid->charFirst`, which only has space for 16 bytes.
   
   This overwrite destroys the `structCharVoid->voidSecond` pointer, replacing
   it with bytes from `SRC_STR`. When line 45 attempts to use
   `structCharVoid->voidSecond` to print a string, it uses this corrupted value
   (seen in the backtrace as `0x3736353433323130`, which is the ASCII
   representation of "76543210"), leading to the segmentation fault.
   
   ### Recommendation
   
   The fix is to ensure that `memcpy` does not exceed the size of the
   destination buffer.
   
   ##### Recommendation
   Change line 42 in `/root/chatdbgpro/bench/cases/external/juliet-cwe122-char-
   type-overrun-memcpy-01/program.c` from:
   
   ```c
   memcpy(structCharVoid->charFirst, SRC_STR, sizeof(*structCharVoid));
   ```
   
   to:
   
   ```c
   memcpy(structCharVoid->charFirst, SRC_STR, sizeof(structCharVoid->charFirst) - 1);
   ```
   
   And ensure the null terminator is placed correctly (line 43 already does
   this, but note it currently assigns `'0'` instead of `'\0'`):
   
   ```c
   structCharVoid->charFirst[(sizeof(structCharVoid->charFirst)/sizeof(char))-1] = '\0';
